# Version source overrides

For some images, the container registry doesn't cleanly expose what version you're actually running. The *Arr stack (Sonarr, Radarr, etc.) wraps upstream apps with their own build numbers like `4.0.17.2952-ls309`. cAdvisor moved registries. Grafana publishes clean tags but no manifest dates.

For these cases, docker-scanner can look up the authoritative version at the upstream project's GitHub releases instead of the registry.

## Bundled defaults

docker-scanner ships with overrides for common home-server images. These work out of the box — no configuration needed. Current defaults cover:

- **LinuxServer wrappers:** `sonarr`, `radarr`, `prowlarr`, `bazarr`, `lidarr`, `readarr`
- **Monitoring:** `cadvisor`, `grafana`
- **Other:** `open-webui`, `ollama`

The authoritative list is in [`pkg/overrides/defaults.yml`](../pkg/overrides/defaults.yml).

## Custom overrides

To override the bundled defaults or add your own, create an overrides file:

```bash
mkdir -p ~/.config/docker-scanner
nano ~/.config/docker-scanner/overrides.yml
```

### Lookup order

Highest precedence first:

1. `-overrides PATH` flag
2. `$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/docker-scanner/overrides.yml`
3. `~/.config/docker-scanner/overrides.yml`
4. Bundled defaults (embedded in the binary)

If you provide your own file, it **replaces** the bundled defaults entirely. To extend rather than replace, copy the bundled defaults as a starting point:

```bash
curl -o ~/.config/docker-scanner/overrides.yml \
  https://raw.githubusercontent.com/tresero/docker-scanner/main/pkg/overrides/defaults.yml
```

Then edit to add your own entries.

## File format

```yaml
overrides:
  - image: docker.io/grafana/grafana
    source: github_release
    repo: grafana/grafana

  - image: lscr.io/linuxserver/sonarr
    source: github_release
    repo: Sonarr/Sonarr
```

| Field | Description |
| --- | --- |
| `image` | Exact match against the image's `registry/name` from your compose file |
| `source` | Only `github_release` is supported in v1 |
| `repo` | The GitHub `owner/repo` to query |

## GitHub rate limits

Anonymous GitHub API requests are limited to 60/hour. Most home-server scans fit easily. For larger fleets, set a `GITHUB_TOKEN` env var (5000/hour authenticated):

```bash
export GITHUB_TOKEN=ghp_yourtoken
./docker-scanner -dir ~/docker-projects
```

A read-only [fine-grained personal access token](https://github.com/settings/tokens?type=beta) with public-repo access is sufficient.

## Limitations

These are known limitations of the v1 implementation. Some will be addressed in v2.

### No `💥` or `⬇️` markers on override results

Upstream version strings like `4.0.17.2952` don't parse as semver, so the major-jump and downgrade comparisons are skipped. The recommendation is shown but without the warning markers.

### Pre-release filter is off for overrides

Some projects label every release as "pre-release" on GitHub (Sonarr, Radarr). Filtering pre-releases would silently break those projects entirely. v1 doesn't filter; v2 may add branch-aware filtering.

### Upstream version may not match registry tag

The override tells you what version exists upstream, but the registry's tag format may differ:

- **LinuxServer** images use `-lsXXX` suffixes (e.g., upstream `4.0.17.2952` → registry `4.0.17.2952-ls309`)
- **cAdvisor** moved from `gcr.io/cadvisor/cadvisor:v0.56.2` to `ghcr.io/google/cadvisor:0.56.2` (no `v` prefix)
- **ollama** publishes upstream as `v0.21.2`, registry as `0.21.2` (no `v`)

When pasting the recommended version into your compose file, you may need to adjust to match what the registry actually accepts.

## Falling back to the registry

If an override fails (GitHub unreachable, repo renamed, no eligible release), the scanner falls back to registry-based detection automatically. In verbose mode, you'll see why:

```
Using override (github_release → Sonarr/Sonarr) for lscr.io/linuxserver/sonarr
Override failed for lscr.io/linuxserver/sonarr, falling back to registry: ...
```